refrain from Vulgar Latin refringere repeat and later from Old French refraindre the line lines that are repeated music poetry the chorus song Poetic fixed forms that feature refrains include the villanelle the virelay and the sestina The use refrains particularly associated with where the versechorusverse song structure typically places refrain almost each and every song The refrain chorus often sharply contrasts the verse melodically rhythmically and harmonically and assumes higher level dynamics and activity often with added instrumentation Chorus form strophic form sectional andor additive way structuring piece music based the repetition one formal section block played repeatedly music refrain has two parts the lyrics the song and the melody Sometimes refrains vary their words slightly when repeated recognizability given the refrain the fact that always sung the same tune and the rhymes present are preserved despite the variations the words Such refrain featured The StarSpangled Banner which contains refrain which introduced different phrase each verse but which always ends similar refrain found the Battle Hymn the Republic which affirms successive verses that Our God His Truth marching Refrains usually but not always come the end the verse Some songs especially ballads incorporate refrains burdens into each verse For example one version the traditional ballad The Cruel Sister includes refrain midverse Note the refrain Lay the Bent the Bonny Broom not traditionally associated with the ballad The Cruel Sister Child This was the work popfolk group Pentangle their 1970 Cruel Sister which has subsequently been picked many folk singers being traditional Both the melody and the refrain come from the ballad known Riddles Wisely Expounded Child 1citation needed Here the refrain syntactically independent the narrative poem the song and has obvious relationship its subject and indeed little inherent meaning all The device can also convey material which relates the subject